For example, if you want to execute the command
flare-otf otf_train.yaml
where flare-otf is the actual executable and otf_train.yaml is the input parameter

we can do this:
nohup flare-otf otf_train.yaml > output.log 2>&1 &

Explanation: The standard output is redirected to the output.log file (if not specified, the default is nohup.out). 
2>&1 redirects standard error to the same file as well, so all output is recorded in output.log. 
The last symbol & puts the command in the background.

After execution, it will display something like: 
[1] 12346


which shows the process id of that execution


we can close the terminal and open it again, and try to check if the process is still there
ps aux | grep flare-otf

this will display all the recently running commands that contains the string flare-otf

